So I had a look at the stream teams which had been on my feed, I go to their respective twitch pages and at least 90% of the streamers were afab. The problem here isn't that there are loads of afab streamers, but there aren't enough AMAB and TMA streamers there.

Everyday I log onto twitch, twitter, tiktok and the rest, where I work on curating feeds which are centred around queer folk. The more time that passes in these spaces the more the non-binary representation consists of only TME people. People who don't share my experiences.

With that said as I saw all the announcements from mutuals this morning something left me ill at ease. I noticed that every announcement on my feed was from TME individuals. I think TMA experiences are of increasing importance of if you want to represent the non-binary community

Remember, that regardless of any way we choose to describe ourselves we are our own people, and our experiences are our own. The neurodivergent community is large, expansive and is supposed to be a broad church. And finally; diversity in how we work is actually an amazing thing.

Following on from that, a lot of the problems that we deal with are simply existing in a world that is designed for the most common neurotype, and being taught in systems designed for that same neurotype. This often results in life-long issues for us.

Remember that the intent of the paradigm is to allow for self-advocacy, autonomy and equity. If you wish to use the paradigm, it's key to remember that while people still struggle, that's their personal struggle, they are not "less abled" or unfortunate, or an inspiration.

However, if a person only refers to them self as neurodivergent, do not ask how about their neurotype, it's rude, and they are not entitled to tell you about this, so avoid putting others in this situation.

Referring to others: approach this on a case by case basis, figure out what a person is comfortable with. If a person solely refers to themselves as autistic, they may not align with the movement, feel free to ask.

What if your neurotype is diverges from the societal norm in multiple ways? That's when the term multiply neurodivergence comes in. As an example, a person with both ADHD and Anxiety is multiply neurodivergent, and these things often come hand in hand.
Neurodiverse isn't a noun, though, so you need to clarify if you're talking about a person. And neurodivergent is both a noun and adjective.

So, you can describe ppl as neurodiverse, or neurodivergent. Somebody who isn't neurodiverse is neurotypical. What makes a person neurodiverse or neurotypical is their neurotype. As an example we can model autism as a neurotype within the paradigm.
